API stands for Application Programming Interface.

It is a bridge that allows two software applications to communicate and exchange data with each other.

Simple Example

Imagine you're at a restaurant:

👨‍🍳 Kitchen = Server (does the work)
🙋 Waiter = API
🧑 Customer = Application/User

You tell the waiter what food you want. The waiter takes your order to the kitchen and brings the food back to you.

Similarly:

Your app sends a request to the API.
The API sends the request to the server.
The server processes it and sends the response back through the API.
Example in AI Translation

Suppose you build an English to Hindi Translator.

Without API

The translation model runs on your own computer.

With API

Your app sends the English text to a translation API.
The API translates it using a powerful AI model.
The translated Hindi text is returned to your application.
Your App
    │
    ▼
Translation API
    │
    ▼
AI Model
    │
    ▼
Hindi Translation
Real-World APIs
🌤️ Weather API – Get live weather information.
💳 Payment API – Process online payments (Stripe, Razorpay).
🗺️ Google Maps API – Show maps and locations.
🤖 OpenAI API – Generate text, summarize, answer questions.
🌐 Google Translate API – Translate text between languages.
📧 Gmail API – Read and send emails.
🎥 YouTube API – Access videos and channel information.

====

import requests

url = "https://api.example.com/translate"

data = {

    "text": "Hello",
    "source": "en",
    "target": "hi"
}

response = requests.post(url, json=data)

print(response.json())

=========

An API (Application Programming Interface) is a set of rules that enables different software applications to communicate and exchange data or services with each other.

Examples you use every day:

Logging in with Google
Checking weather in a mobile app
Paying through UPI
Booking an Uber ride
Translating text with Google Translate

All of these work because applications communicate using APIs.

